{"id":"2210.15579","submitter":"Anurag Kaushal","authors":"Adwait Gaikwad, Anurag Kaushal, Gautam Mandal and Spenta R. Wadia","title":"A Microscopic Model of Black Hole Evaporation in Two Dimensions","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"hep-th cond-mat.stat-mech","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We present a microscopic model of black hole (BH) `evaporation' in\nasymptotically $AdS_2$ spacetimes dual to the low energy sector of the SYK\nmodel. To describe evaporation, the SYK model is coupled to a bath comprising\nof $N_f$ free scalar fields $\\Phi_i$. We consider couplings of the form\n$O_{SYK}(t) \\Phi_i(0,t)$ where $O_{SYK}$ involves the Kourkoulou-Maldacena\noperator $i J/N \\sum_{k=1}^{N/2} s'_k \\psi_{2k-1}(t) \\psi_{2k}(t)$ specified by\na spin vector $s'$, or products of such operators. We discuss the time\nevolution of a product of (i) a pure state of the SYK, namely a BH microstate\ncharacterized by a spin vector $s$ and an effective BH temperature $T_{BH}$ and\n(ii) a Calabrese-Cardy state of the bath characterized by an effective\ntemperature $T_{bath}$. We take $T_{bath}\\ll T_{BH}$, and $T_{BH}$ much lower\nthan the UV scale $J$ of the SYK model, allowing a description in terms of the\ntime reparameterization mode. Tracing over the bath leads to a Feynman-Vernon\ntype effective action for the SYK model, which we study in the large $N$, low\nenergy limit. The leading large $N$ behaviour of the time reparameterization\nmode is found, as well as the $O(1/\\sqrt N)$ fluctuations. The latter are\ncharacterized by a non-Markovian non-linear stochastic differential equation\nwith non-local Gaussian noise. At large times we find two classes of solutions\n(a) and (b) which asymptotically approach, respectively, a BH at a lower\ntemperature, and a horizonless geometry; we identify the processes in (a) and\n(b) with partial and complete BH evaporation. Importantly, the asymptotic\nsolution in both cases involves the scalar product of the spin vectors $s.s'$,\nwhich carries some information about the initial state. We show how, by\nrepeating the dynamical process $O(N^2)$ times with different choices of the\nspin vector $s'$, one can in principle have a reconstruction of the initial BH\nmicrostate.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 27 Oct 2022 16:15:49 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-10-28"}
